#Title 
Set Up SSH Key Authentication on a Linux Server
#Purpose
This SOP is meant for people who need to set up an ssh connection between two Linux environments.
#Scope
This applies to Linux system administrators and will cover the steps required to
1.	Prepare the Linux environment for remote administration
2.	Install the ssh key service
3.	Generate keys
4.	Utilize the generated keys for remote access
#Definitions
Ip address= internet protocol address
Ssh= secure shell
Username= the username of the Linux machine
Remote_server_ip=the ip address of the remote server
/path/tp/private_key= the file path that you saved your private key to
#Procedure steps
Step 1: Install and verify the SSH service
Install the OpenSSH server and run it on your linux machine.
•	sudo dnf install openssh-server
Enter root password when prompted.
•	sudo systemctl enable –now sshd 
Step 2:set ip ip address 
Find your network interface using the following command on both machines
•	ip a
Step 3: Configure basic firewall access for SSH
A firewall must be active but allow ssh traffic.
•	sudo firewall-cmd  --permanent  --add-services=ssh
•	sudo firewall-cmd --reload

Step 4:key generation
Generate an ssh key on the linux client.
•	ssh-keygen -t ed25519
Click enter to save the key to the default file.
Press enter two more times to leave the passphrase empty as we do not want a passphrase.
You will now get your randomart image of the key.

Now copy the public key to your server.
•	ssh-copy-id username@remote_server_ip
Type yes when prompted to continue connecting.
Enter password at the password prompt.
Now the server has the ssh key.

Step 5: edit configuration
Enter the ssh daemon file on the Linux server for configuration.
•	sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Enter root passwort at the prompt.
Locate the following lines and change them as required.
•	PermitRootLogin no
•	PasswordAuthentication no
•	PubkeyAuthentication yes
Press control and X to exit and Y to save and enter to select the file to save the configuration under.
Check for syntax errors so you do not lock yourself out of a machine.
•	Sudo sshd -t
Enter password at the password prompt.
Reload the ssh service to apply changes.
•	Sudo systemctl reload ssh

Step 6: ssh using private key
Log into the Linux server from the client using your private key
•	Ssh -I /path/tp/private_key username@Remote_server_ip
Exit from the server.
•	Exit
Step 7: verify public key
Log into the server from the client.
•	Ssh username@Remote_server_ip
Once you have entered the server exit out.
•	Exit


#Troubleshooting
The following commands are used to verify and test common connectivity problems.
•	systemctl status ssh
Checks if ssh service is active, failing, or stopped.
•	ping -c 4 remote_server_ip
Checks if the linux machines can communicate with each other.
•	ssh-keygen -p -f path/tp/private_key
Allows you to change your passphrase.


#Security Consiterations
•	sudo ss -tupln
Shows open ports.


